        "highlight_label": "fewer traffic accidents per vehicle"
      },
      {
        "type": "narrative",
        "heading": "Road Accidents Peaked Around 2001",
        "body": "In the chart below, you see the number of accidents per 1,000 vehicles initially rising to a peak in 2001, where it hit 50.9. However, from that year, there has been a noticeable decline, dropping 48% to 26.3 by 2019. This reduction reflects enhanced road safety measures and more cautious driving behaviors.",
        "viz_index": 0
      },
      {
        "type": "narrative",
        "heading": "Rise in Vehicle Numbers with Better Safety",
        "body": "Interestingly, while the number of vehicles on the road increased by over 56% from 2000 to 2019, the rate of accidents per vehicle fell. This trend shows that even as more cars are introduced, road safety protocols and driver education are making a real difference.",
        "viz_index": 1
      },
      {
        "type": "narrative",
        "heading": "Reduction in Road Casualties",
        "body": "The decline in traffic accidents goes hand-in-hand with improved safety outcomes. The number of injuries per 1,000 vehicles dropped by 65%, and fatalities have completely diminished to zero by 2019 from a peak in the early 2000s. These indicators suggest an overall safer driving environment in Reykjavík.",
        "viz_index": 3
      },
      {
        "type": "narrative",
        "heading": "A Positive Outlook for the Future",
        "body": "For residents, this means safer journeys on the roads of Reykjavík. The reductions in accidents and injuries provide reassurance that ongoing safety measures are effective. These trends also highlight the importance of maintaining and improving these efforts to ensure continued progress."
      }
